                <option value="none">Choose one...</option>
                <option value="nothought">Don't think about it</option>
                <option value="ignore">Try to ignore it</option>
                <option value="agony">Agonize over it</option>
                <option value="emphasis">Place emphasis on it</option>
                {{/select}}
            </select>

        </div>

        <div class="tab" data-tab="tab8" data-group="primary-tabs">

            <h2>The Body</h2>
            <p>To construct a fear of the body,carefully consider what your character feels is important and what they would do to protect that.</p>
            <p>One of the most obvious fears to confront an adventurer with is that of physical harm. After all, a huge portion of the job is risking danger. Pain and death are obvious and appropriate fear that most adventurers will face often.</p>
            <select name="flags.detailedcharinfo.bodyfear" value="{{flags.detailedcharinfo.bodyfear}}" id="bodyfear">
                {{#select flags.detailedcharinfo.bodyfear}}
                <option value="Choose one...">Choose one...</option>
                <option value="Pain">Pain</option>
                <option value="Weakness">Weakness</option>
                <option value="Injury">Injury</option>
                <option value="Sickness">Sickness</option>
                <option value="Death">Death</option>
                {{/select}}
            </select>

            <hr />
            <br />

            <h2>The Mind</h2>
            <p>To create a mind-based fear for your character, consider what you know and focus on the dangers you find most important. </p>
            <p>The most powerful tool any adventurer has in their arsenal is thier mind, since it controls how they put thier skills to use. It can also work against them, constructing invisible enemies and threats out of harmless things.</p>
            <select name="flags.detailedcharinfo.mindfear" value="{{flags.detailedcharinfo.mindfear}}" id="mindfear">
                {{#select flags.detailedcharinfo.mindfear}}
                <option value="Choose one...">Choose one...</option>
                <option value="Anxiety">Anxiety</option>
                <option value="Lack of preparation">Lack of preparation</option>
                <option value="Feeling lost">Feeling lost</option>
                <option value="Post-traumatic stress">Post-traumatic stress</option>
                <option value="Lack of valuable information">Lack of valuable information</option>
                <option value="Existential dread">Existential dread</option>
                {{/select}}
            </select>

            <hr />
            <br />

            <h2>The Soul</h2>
            <p>To construct a spiritual fear, ask difficult questions about your character's beliefs and behavior.</p>
            <p>A story about good and evil on a conceptual level ecomes more grounded when you have a character embody those concepts. Evil is very easy to understand when it can swing a sword at you. Fearing personal corruption is a great way to add weight to actions and decisions your character must make.</p>
            <select name="flags.detailedcharinfo.soulfear" value="{{flags.detailedcharinfo.soulfear}}" id="soulfear">
                {{#select flags.detailedcharinfo.soulfear}}
                <option value="Choose one...">Choose one...</option>
                <option value="The nature of evil">The nature of evil</option>
                <option value="The fragility of virtue">The fragility of virtue</option>
                <option value="A specific evil person">A specific evil person</option>
                <option value="Personal corruption">Personal corruption</option>
                <option value="Crisis of faith">Crisis of faith</option>
                <option value="Cosmic horror a la H.P. Lovecraft">Cosmic horror a la H.P. Lovecraft</option>
                {{/select}}
            </select>

            <hr />
            <br />

            <h2>The Heart</h2>
            <p>To construct a fear of the heart, focus on social interaction and what would happen if something went wrong.</p>
            <p>Adding features like tusks, tails, and otherworldly fire to other characters or NPCs (non-player characters) makes differences more overt and easier to play with.</p>
            <select name="flags.detailedcharinfo.heartfear" value="{{flags.detailedcharinfo.heartfear}}" id="heartfear">
                {{#select flags.detailedcharinfo.heartfear}}
                <option value="Choose one...">Choose one...</option>
                <option value="Rejection">Rejection</option>
                <option value="Intimacy">Intimacy</option>
                <option value="Loneliness">Loneliness</option>
                <option value="Personal awkwardness">Personal awkwardness</option>
                <option value="Loss">Loss</option>
                <option value="Social pressures to succeed">Social pressures to succeed</option>
                {{/select}}
            </select>

            <hr />
            <br />

            <h2>The Beast</h2>
            <p>To construct a fear of the beast think what your character does not know and find a way to make that dangerous.</p>
            <p>The most obvious manifestation of the beast is monsters: the awful things that lurk in dungeons with sharp teeth and steely claws. Almost every creature found in a monster manual, or bestiary, is individually terrifying, and it is easy to empathize with a character who sees monsters that way.</p>
            <select name="flags.detailedcharinfo.beastfear" value="{{flags.detailedcharinfo.beastfear}}" id="beastfear">
                {{#select flags.detailedcharinfo.beastfear}}
